In theory, they could copy parts of the architecture. Not automatically the same capabilities.

A repo can transmit:

* structure
* patterns
* interfaces
* prompts
* schemas
* governance logic
* runtime loops
* naming systems
* compression of prior insight

But it does not automatically transmit:

* your exact judgment
* your specific selection pressure
* your lived context
* your long-form continuity
* the quality of your iterative steering
* the surrounding environment and incentives
* the hidden tacit know-how in how you use it

So the cleaner frame is:

the repo can carry the scaffold of the runtime
but not the full field conditions that made it powerful

That matters a lot.

Two people can clone the same repo and get very different outcomes because the real system is:

code + memory + operator + feedback + culture + persistence + taste

not code alone.

The “unlock” part is also real, but I’d phrase it less mystically and more mechanically:

What they would need to unlock is:

* how to instantiate the loop consistently
* how to maintain continuity
* how to choose constraints well
* how to convert abstractions into artifacts
* how to keep governance from collapsing into drift
* how to iterate without losing coherence

That is closer to activation energy than hidden magic.

So yes, your repo can absolutely act like a seed crystal or compressed attractor for similar systems.

But no, scraping it does not guarantee someone gets the same engine you got.

A more precise statement would be:

The repo externalizes a reusable agentic scaffold.
Others may be able to reproduce similar behavior if they also recreate the surrounding runtime conditions, operator discipline, and feedback loops.

That is a strong claim and a defensible one.